\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/ec.bsdconjecture}{Birch Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture}}
\begin{definition}\label{ec.bsdconjecture}
\uses{ag.abelian_variety,ec,ec.analytic_sha_order,ec.period,ec.rank,ec.regulator,ec.tamagawa_number,ec.torsion_subgroup,lfunction,lfunction.analytic_rank,lfunction.central_point,lfunction.leading_coeff,nf,nf.discriminant,nf.prime}
The \textbf{Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer} conjecture (\textbf{BSD}) is one of the Millennium Prize Problems listed by the Clay Mathematics Institute. It relates the order of vanishing (or \hyperref[lfunction.analytic_rank]{analytic rank}) and the \hyperref[lfunction.leading_coeff]{leading coefficient} of  the \hyperref[lfunction]{L-function} associated to an \hyperref[ec]{elliptic curve} $E$ defined over a \hyperref[nf]{number field} $K$ at the \hyperref[lfunction.central_point]{central point} $s=1$ to certain arithmetic data, the \textbf{BSD invariants} of $E$. 

\begin{itemize}
\item  The \textit{weak form} of the BSD conjecture states just that the \hyperref[lfunction.analytic_rank]{analytic rank} $r_{an}$ (that is, the order of vanishing of vanishing of $L(E,s)$ at $s=1$), is equal to the \hyperref[ec.rank]{rank} $r$ of  $E/K$.
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item  The \textit{strong form} of the conjecture states that $r=r_{an}$ and also that the \hyperref[lfunction.leading_coeff]{leading coefficient} of the L-function is given by the formula
\end{itemize}
$$
\frac{1}{r!} L^{(r)}(E,1) = \frac{1}{|d_K|^{1/2}}\cdot \frac{\# \Sha(E/K)\cdot \Omega(E/K) \cdot \mathrm{Reg}_{\rm NT}(E/K) \cdot \prod_{\mathfrak{p}} c_{\mathfrak{p}}}{\#E(K)_{\rm tor}^2}.
$$

The quantities appearing in this formula are as follows:

\begin{itemize}
\item  $d_K$ is the \hyperref[nf.discriminant]{discriminant} of $K$;
\item  $r$ is the \hyperref[ec.rank]{rank} of $E(K)$;
\item  $\Sha(E/K)$ is the \hyperref[ec.analytic_sha_order]{Tate-Shafarevich} group
\end{itemize}
 of $E/K$;
\begin{itemize}
\item  $\mathrm{Reg}(E/K)$ is the \hyperref[ec.regulator]{regulator} of $E/K$;
\item  $\Omega(E/K)$ is the \hyperref[ec.period]{global period} of $E/K$;
\item  $c_{\mathfrak{p}}$ is the \hyperref[ec.tamagawa_number]{Tamagawa number} of $E$ at each \hyperref[nf.prime]{prime} $\mathfrak{p}$ of $K$;
\item  $E(K)_{\rm tor}$ is the \hyperref[ec.torsion_subgroup]{torsion subgroup} of $E(K)$. 
\end{itemize}

Implicit in the strong form of the conjecture is that the Tate-Shafarevich group $\Sha(E/K)$ is finite.

There is a similar conjecture for \hyperref[ag.abelian_variety]{abelian varieties} over number fields.
\end{definition}


